•	Model Year vs Price: a clear upward trend was observed with average prices rising sharply for recent model years, with an extreme jump from vehicles that are from 2018 or newer

•	Brand vs Price: The 10 most expressive brands by average price were dominated by luxury and exotic brands, with the average price several times higher than regular brands.

•	Fuel Type vs Price: Electric and premium-fuel vehicles were higher in price; standard gas vehicles showed the widest price range across the dataset.






Limitations, Ethics, Reflection
Limitations:
1.	Feature Scope: only four features were used for modeling. There are many features in this dataset like torque, Drivetrain, Body Type, and reliability rating which we did not include and likely account for the remaining 9% of unexplained variance.
2.	Price type: The dataset reflect listed prices, not final sale or transaction prices. Actual prices may differ due to negotiation, dealer markups, or market conditions so its important to keep these factors in mind.
3.	Dataset time range: Vehicles from earlier model years (pre-2010) may be underrepresented here which could potentially show bias in our Model year predictor toward more recent vehicles
4.	Web scraped Data: Because this dataset was web scraped, there may be inconsistencies in how different listing sources report features like fuel type or horsepower.
5.	Generalization: This model was trained on listings from a specific period and geographic context and should not be expected to generalize reliability to other markets or future pricing conditions and instead should be used to get a general idea.
Ethical Considerations
Our model weighs brand heavily in price prediction so it may encode and reinforce existing market bias and confirm that certain manufacturers are worth more regardless of the quality of their vehicles. If this model were to be deployed in the real world it could harm buyers of lower costing used vehicles by making certain brands seem more costly than they should be. Any real-world application should include transparency about what the model can and cannot account for and be tested by numerous people.
Reflection:
This project shows that a set of four variables can explain over 90% of used car price variation when the right model is applied. The most surprising finding was how little fuel_type feature importance was compared to the other three variables because I thought that with the rise of EVs and hybrids, fuel type would be a strong differentiator, but we were wrong. If we decided to do more with this project, we would incorporate more features to account for the other 9% of variance and fine tune our model more to get even better numbers than what we have now. We would also experiment with larger, more geographically diverse datasets to improve generalization.

